<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO:; cp,11 Adams is the closet thing we have today to a star composer  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN THE heyday of Verdi, Rossini and Puccini, opera houses vied to perform the
star composers' latest works before the clamoring public.;    One man commands
that kind of attention today: Berkeley's John Adams, whose 1991 opera "The
Death of Klinghoffer" was booked by six opera houses before the first
rehearsal started.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OPERA'S YOUNG BRIGHT HOPE TO TAKE BOWS AT
CABRILLO  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  PERFORMANCE  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Earlier this month the low-key, local-boy-turned-star <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> was back home
briefly between conducting the <LOCATION>Cleveland Orchestra</LOCATION> and recording his opera
with the <ORGANIZATION>Opera de Lyon</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>. It's that kind of life now: commissions,
major engagements, jet commutes, 15-hour days.;    At 44, <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> still manages
the aw-shucks, pebble-kicking quality that has endeared him to the Bay Area
musical community since joining the <ORGANIZATION>San Francisco Conservatory of Music</ORGANIZATION>
faculty in <DATE>1972.</DATE>;    Music macabre;  Now it's Cabrillo's turn. In the biggest
coup since engaging Music Director <PERSON>Dennis Russell Davies</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Cabrillo Music
Festival</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION> has <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> on the podium for two weeks during <PERSON>Davies</PERSON>'
sabbatical year.;    The kind of audacity marking <PERSON>Adams</PERSON>' guest-conducting
programs around the country is being carried over to <LOCATION>Cabrillo</LOCATION>. Few
composer-conductors have the panache to open their festival with such morbid
morsels as their own "Aria of the Falling Body," and close with <ORGANIZATION>Mahler</ORGANIZATION>'s
"Songs on the Death of Children" and <PERSON>Britten</PERSON>'s "Sinfonia da requiem," after
several equally lugubrious selections.;    The edge of the new;  While <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Mahler</PERSON> and <PERSON>Britten</PERSON> all get attention, the Cabrillo focus is on newer music, in
which the composer-conductor offers special insights, <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> points out.;   
"It's helpful on both sides. My composing informs my conducting. When doing
music of other composers, I have a different intuition.;    "Also my
conducting informs my composing -- I'm aware of necessities, of what
instruments can and cannot do, and what can be done in limited rehearsal
time.";    The <DATE>1991</DATE> Cabrillo sojourn getting into full swing tonight could be
termed a season of mystical horizons. It offers <PERSON>Britten</PERSON>'s songs on <PERSON>William
Blake</PERSON>, <PERSON>Adams</PERSON>' stunning vocal concert piece "The Wound-Dresser," his own
orchestration of Liszt's "The Black Gondola" (a preview of his
premiere-studded <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> Symphony program in the fall), part of
<PERSON>Britten</PERSON>'s "Kingdom of the Pagodas," and <PERSON>Milhaud</PERSON>'s "The Creation of the World"
(danced by <ORGANIZATION>Tandy Beal &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>).;    Overriding it all is the shadow of <PERSON>Adams</PERSON>'
opera, "The Death of Klinghoffer," a work based on the Palestinian hijacking
of the "Achille Lauro" cruise ship in the <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION> in <DATE>1985</DATE>. The work will
not reach the <LOCATION>San Francisco Opera</LOCATION> until <DATE>November 1992</DATE>, but Cabrillo scheduled
excerpts and offers performances by its title-role singer, baritone <PERSON>Sanford
Sylvan.</PERSON>;    Because of the opera, a <ORGANIZATION>Middle Eastern</ORGANIZATION> theme overlays the concerts
the <DATE>second weekend</DATE>, with <PERSON>Nazim Ozel</PERSON> on Turkish flute and "semi-civilized tree"
(a custom-made, plucked musical instrument) <DATE>Aug. 3</DATE>, and a collaboration by
<ORGANIZATION>Group Parvaneh</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Ballet Afsaneh</ORGANIZATION> with Turkish and Persian music and dance
<DATE>Aug. 4.</DATE>;    Modern melodies;  But nothing is a one-man show, not even with
<PERSON>Adams</PERSON> around. Music Director <PERSON>Davies</PERSON> collaborated via long distance in the
programming decisions. <PERSON>JoAnn Falletta</PERSON> leads the juried concert of music by
living <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> composers <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, with pieces by <PERSON>Ross Bauer</PERSON>,
<PERSON>David Jaffe</PERSON>, <PERSON>Stefan Carow</PERSON>, <PERSON>Allen Shearer</PERSON> and "the other" <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>, <PERSON>John
Luther</PERSON> Adams.;    This Cabrillo season features prominent soloists such as
violinist <PERSON>Stephanie Chase</PERSON> and pianist <PERSON>Richard Goode</PERSON>, and finally what may be
an end to the nomadic Cabrillo life: an entry into the <ORGANIZATION>Santa Cruz Civic
Auditorium</ORGANIZATION>, thanks to a <MONEY>$35,000</MONEY> renovation. The face-lift instantly converts
the 1,950-seat hall into a 970-seat concert site with new lighting, sound
system, grid and proscenium. All the concerts (except <DATE>Aug. 28</DATE>) are being held
at the auditorium.;     <ORGANIZATION>Cabrillo Music Festival</ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON> and <PERSON>JoAnn
Falletta</PERSON>, guest conductors; Where: <LOCATION>Santa Cruz Civic Auditorium</LOCATION>; When: Nightly
Thursdays-Sundays through <DATE>Aug. 4</DATE>, with weekend matinees. Also this <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at
<LOCATION>San Juan Bautista</LOCATION>. No repeat concerts.; Tickets: <MONEY>$15.50</MONEY>-<MONEY>$23.50</MONEY>. (408) 429-3444.  </TEXT>
