<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Herbert Blomstedt will move the S.F. Symphony to the Civic
Auditorium for two weeks next season, while renovation work is done on Davies
hall.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE San Francisco Symphony announced plans for its 80th season (1991-92)
Tuesday, and with the announcement came news that major acoustic renovations
at the orchestra's home, Davies Symphony Hall, will cause disruptions at
season's end.;    Because of the Davies reconstruction, the symphony will move
into the Civic Auditorium during its last two subscription weeks (May 20-29,
1992).  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DAVIES WORK DISRUPTS S.F. SYMPHONY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Classical Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "That is why we want to give the <ORGANIZATION>Verdi 'Requiem</ORGANIZATION>' then -- it's the place for
a big sound," explained Music Director <PERSON>Herbert Blomstedt</PERSON> yesterday from his
home in <LOCATION>Lucerne</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Switzerland.</LOCATION>;    Recording postponed;    The annual May
recordings with <ORGANIZATION>London Records</ORGANIZATION> will have to be postponed until <DATE>fall 1992</DATE>. And
for one week in <DATE>May</DATE> the orchestra will be silent, right after its three-week
Asian tour.;    <ORGANIZATION>Blomstedt</ORGANIZATION> will be on the podium for 15 instead of the usual 16
weeks because of that <DATE>May week</DATE> without programs. Three of his weeks on the
podium will be during the Asian tour.;    The ambitious program, <PERSON>Blomstedt</PERSON>
says, serves his goal "to give everybody a new and fresh experience" in the
concert hall.;    Some highlights:;    (box) The season opens with a gala
<DATE>Sept. 4</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>Davies</ORGANIZATION>, with coloratura soprano <PERSON>Kathleen Battle</PERSON> singing <PERSON>Richard
Strauss</PERSON> and works by <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON> and Berlioz.;    (box) Guest conductor <PERSON>David
Zinman</PERSON>, who is looking more and more like a fixture here, will return for two
weeks. Other guest conductors include <PERSON>Roger Norrington</PERSON>, <PERSON>Eduardo Mata</PERSON>, <PERSON>Christof
Perick</PERSON>, composer <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>, <PERSON>Iona Brown</PERSON>, <PERSON>Michael Tilson Thomas</PERSON>, <PERSON>Kent Nagano</PERSON>,
<PERSON>John Nelson</PERSON>, <PERSON>Neal Stulberg</PERSON> and <PERSON>Silvain Cambreling</PERSON>. Conducting during two weeks
of subscription concerts, each, are <PERSON>Semyon Bychkov</PERSON>, <PERSON>Gunther Herbig</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Alasdair Neale.</PERSON>;    (box) <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> audiences will hear the large-scale <PERSON>Charles
Ives Symphony</PERSON> No. 4. This American answer to <ORGANIZATION>Mahler</ORGANIZATION>'s symphonies, which dates
back to the World War I era, will be given under <PERSON>Michael Tilson Thomas</PERSON>, <DATE>Nov.
20-23</DATE>, with the symphony chorus.;    (box) <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>' podium week <DATE>Nov. 13-16</DATE>
will feature the commissioned world premiere of his own "El Dorado.";    (box)
Other commissioned world premieres include <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> composer <PERSON>Charles
Wuorinen</PERSON>'s 35-minute-long "Genesis" on Christian texts, written for chorus and
orchestra, and <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> composer <PERSON>Wayne Peterson</PERSON>'s "The Face of <TIME>Night</TIME>, the
Heart of the Dark.";    (box) Other music by living composers includes various
pieces by <PERSON>Henri Dutilleux</PERSON>, <PERSON>Christopher Rouse</PERSON>'s "Iscariot," <PERSON>Alfred Schnittke</PERSON>'s
"(K)ein Sommernachtstraum," <PERSON>Joan Tower</PERSON>'s "Sequoia," <PERSON>George Perle</PERSON>'s "Dance
Fantasy" and excerpts from Sir <PERSON>Michael Tippett</PERSON>'s "The Midsummer Marriage.";   
(box) Other unusual repertoire features a program consisting entirely of
<ORGANIZATION>Manuel de Falla</ORGANIZATION>'s music, with "Homenajes" and the opera "La Vida Breve";
<ORGANIZATION>Stravinsky</ORGANIZATION>'s complete "Pulcinella," with voices; <PERSON>Honegger</PERSON>'s "Christmas
Cantata"; <ORGANIZATION>Barber</ORGANIZATION>'s Cello Concerto; <ORGANIZATION>Corigliano</ORGANIZATION>'s Symphony No. 1; and <PERSON>Francaix</PERSON>'s
"The Flower Clock.";    (box) The recording repertory next season with <ORGANIZATION>London
Records</ORGANIZATION> is not all traditional either, with <PERSON>Schubert</PERSON>'s "Great C Major"
Symphony (No. 9), <PERSON>Wagner</PERSON>'s "Siegfried Idyll," <PERSON>Franz Berwald</PERSON>'s "Symphonie
Serieuse," <PERSON>Schubert</PERSON>'s Overture in the Italian Style, and <PERSON>Strauss</PERSON>' tone poem
"Ein Heldenleben" on the agenda.;    (box) Performances of <PERSON>Berlioz</PERSON>'
vocal-dramatic symphony "Romeo et Juliette," under <PERSON>Roger Norrington.</PERSON>;    (box)
Star soloists include pianists <PERSON>Mitsuko Uchida</PERSON>, <PERSON>Horacio Gutierrez</PERSON>, <PERSON>Garrick
Ohlsson</PERSON>, <PERSON>Peter Serkin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Andre Watts</PERSON>; violinist Cho-Liang Lin; and sopranos
<PERSON>Jessye Norman</PERSON>, <PERSON>June Anderson</PERSON> and Dawn Upshaw.;    Special events;    (box)
Special events, guest ensembles and recitals will feature pianist <PERSON>Maurizio
Pollini</PERSON>; the Soviet Philharmonic under <PERSON>Gennady Rozhdestvensky</PERSON>; the <LOCATION>Cleveland
Orchestra</LOCATION> under <PERSON>Christoph von Dohnanyi</PERSON>; the <LOCATION>Minnesota Orchestra</LOCATION> under Edo de
Waart; and the Academy of St. Martin-in-the-Fields.;    (box) The violinists
<PERSON>Itzhak Perlman</PERSON> and <PERSON>Isaac Stern</PERSON> will be back for their near-annual
appearances.;    (box) The symphony will also present the Joffrey Ballet
again, <DATE>June 29-July 12, 1992</DATE>.  </TEXT>
