<LEADPARA>  CANDIDATES for San Jose Symphony's music directorship are being aggressively
courted by rival organizations, just as though they were the most eligible
bachelors at the prom.;    Leonid Grin, the Soviet emigre who scored such a
vibrant success with critics and audiences when he was guest conductor in
February, looked like the front-runner for a similar vacancy at the Spokane,
Wash., Symphony. Spokane reps even traveled to hear him in San Jose, and Grin
went to Spokane to conduct some audition rehearsals.;    But now, amid great
sighs of relief by local symphony-watchers, Spokane has named another Soviet
emigre -- Vakhtang Jordania -- as its music director. So Grin remains in the
running for San Jose -- at least until the next offer pops up on his fax
machine.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GRIN WON'T BE GOING TO SPOKANE
SOVIET STILL IN S.J. SYMPHONY RACE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Classical Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     San Jose already has lost candidate <PERSON>John Mauceri</PERSON>, another preseason
favorite, at least in this critic's view, until his cancellation and
withdrawal last month.;    <LOCATION>BERKELEY</LOCATION> MINIMALIST composer <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>' upcoming
opera may be too political for its own good. Even with the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> war
now over, the work is being treated with extreme caution and special security
measures.;    "The Death of Klinghoffer" is based on the <DATE>1985</DATE> Palestinian
terrorist attack on the <LOCATION>Mediterranean</LOCATION> cruise ship <PERSON>Achille Lauro</PERSON>, which
resulted in the death of one passenger, an escape by air, an interception by
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> jets, and a trial in <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> in which the terrorists were found guilty.;   
The opus may prove as politically sensitive as classics of the genre such as
"The Marriage of Figaro," "Rigoletto" and "Un ballo in maschera.";    Next
week's world premiere in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Belgium</LOCATION>, of this operatic collaboration
between composer <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> and stage director <PERSON>Peter Sellars</PERSON> is being orchestrated
with a news brownout. There are no interviews, and, until two weeks before the
<DATE>March 19</DATE> opening, there were no press releases, either.;    The work, coming
to the <LOCATION>San Francisco Opera</LOCATION> in the <DATE>fall of 1992</DATE>, opens in the <ORGANIZATION>Monnaie Opera
House</ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> in attendance.;    The unsettled world situation is also a
factor in the cancellation of upcoming tours to <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION> by the <LOCATION>New York
Philharmonic</LOCATION> under <PERSON>Zubin Mehta</PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION>St. Louis Symphony</ORGANIZATION> under <PERSON>Leonard
Slatkin</PERSON>. The Philharmonic was to make an Easter tour, while the <LOCATION>St. Louis</LOCATION>
orchestra was to have gone in February.;    THE COMPUTER-MUSIC studio at
<ORGANIZATION>Stanford University</ORGANIZATION> has aroused controversy over a concert coming <DATE>Thursday</DATE>
<TIME>night</TIME> to <ORGANIZATION>Dinkelspiel Auditorium</ORGANIZATION>, because Norwegian composer Per <PERSON>Landa</PERSON> insists
on passing out earplugs for those who will be hearing his high-volume music.; 
  "That (high a sound level) is utterly against my philosophy, but I can't be
tyrannical," says studio director <PERSON>John Chowning</PERSON>. The concert also features
composers from <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and Stanford.;    On a more harmonious note, <PERSON>Chowning</PERSON>
is working to bring over from the <ORGANIZATION>USSR</ORGANIZATION> the legendary <PERSON>Leon Theremin</PERSON>, who
invented one of the first electronic instruments (named the theremin) around
<DATE>1924</DATE>. Chowning met him on his recent Soviet visit and found him spry and
active at 95, eager to return to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, where he had lived for a
time until <DATE>1938</DATE>. Theremin once met with <PERSON>Lenin</PERSON> himself to demonstrate his
instrument and apparently left the Red leader impressed with his revolutionary
device.;    THE DEATH of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> composer <PERSON>Elie Siegmeister</PERSON> at 82 deprives the
music world of a live-wire author, raconteur, educator, and prolific composer
on American themes. He studied abroad with <PERSON>Nadia Boulanger</PERSON> and had his music
played by <PERSON>Arturo Toscanini</PERSON>, who was never known to be a champion of American
music. Five seasons ago the <LOCATION>San Jose Symphony</LOCATION>, under <PERSON>George Cleve</PERSON>, played
<PERSON>Siegmeister</PERSON>'s "Ozark Set."  </TEXT>
