<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Elizabeth Knighton Printy: concussion, broken pelvis, four
broken ribs.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SOPRANO Elizabeth Knighton Printy barely escaped disaster in the scary suicide
scene at the end of a Minnesota Opera production of "Tosca.";   When she
jumped through the window for Tosca's suicide plunge, she missed the bed that
was supposed to catch her, hit her head, and fell off a platform to the floor
22 feet below.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TOSCA'S SUICIDE LEAP NEARLY DOES IN ONE SOPRANO  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Classical Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Undaunted, she expects to perform a stint with the San <PERSON>Jose Symphony</PERSON> next
spring.;   "It was a miracle that I didn't kill myself," she said. The fall
resulted in four broken ribs, a concussion, a broken pelvis and a week in the
hospital.;   After that <DATE>Oct. 24</DATE> mishap at <ORGANIZATION>St. Paul's Ordway Theater</ORGANIZATION>, the
anguished epilogue to her otherwise successful debut as <LOCATION>Tosca</LOCATION>, she is on
crutches but glad there was "no irreparable damage.";   The determined singer
plans to resume her performance schedule in <DATE>January</DATE>, singing the songs of
death in <ORGANIZATION>Shostakovich</ORGANIZATION>'s Symphony No. 14 in <LOCATION>New York City.</LOCATION>;   Now a resident of
<LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Knighton Printy</PERSON> lived in the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> <DATE>from 1976</DATE> to <DATE>'84</DATE>. She sang
in the <ORGANIZATION>Verdi</ORGANIZATION> "Requiem" with the San <PERSON>Jose Symphony</PERSON> last <DATE>spring</DATE> and will return
for the <ORGANIZATION>Mahler Second Symphony</ORGANIZATION>, under <PERSON>George Cleve</PERSON>, in <DATE>June 1992.</DATE>;  
Appropriately, the Mahler symphony is subtitled "Resurrection.";   In other
news of the orchestra, the lineup of vocalists for the <DATE>Dec. 7-8</DATE>
"Messiah"-<PERSON>Mozart Requiem</PERSON> package is superlative: <PERSON>Lorraine Hunt</PERSON>, <PERSON>Wendy
Hillhouse</PERSON>, <PERSON>Robert Tate</PERSON> and <PERSON>William Parker.</PERSON>;   The symphony has also signed
Mexican-born conductor <PERSON>Jorge Perez-Gomez</PERSON> for the <DATE>May 14</DATE> flamenco program at
<ORGANIZATION>Flint Center</ORGANIZATION>. Guitarist Anita Sheer will give the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> premiere of the
"Suite flamenca" by her teacher, <PERSON>Carlos Montoya</PERSON>. She describes it as a
concerto for guitar and orchestra. Choreographer <PERSON>Patri Nader</PERSON> will prepare the
local performers of <ORGANIZATION>Bailes de Espana</ORGANIZATION> in four selections featuring composers
Bizet, <ORGANIZATION>Albeniz</ORGANIZATION>, de Falla and Gimenez.;   <LOCATION>UNITED OPERA</LOCATION> -- The <LOCATION>San Francisco
Opera</LOCATION> wants to do something special for the weeklong celebration in <DATE>June 1995</DATE>
of the 50th anniversary of the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION> charter. A new opera, perhaps.
The company's general director, <PERSON>Lotfi Mansouri</PERSON>, explained: "We hope we can
stimulate a new opera from <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> Rim countries" with a commission.;   NEW
FACES -- The <LOCATION>San Francisco Symphony</LOCATION> has announced an adventurous appointment:
Precocious British composer <PERSON>George Benjamin</PERSON>, 31, will lead Wet Ink, a
new-music series featuring six <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> premieres, from <DATE>Feb. 7</DATE> to <DATE>Feb. 28</DATE>. The
series will replace the New and Unusual Music series, which was led by
composer-in-residence <PERSON>George Perle</PERSON>, 76.;   The symphony may also be
cultivating a special relationship with frequent guest conductor <PERSON>David Zinman</PERSON>.
After prolonged stints this year and last, <PERSON>Zinman</PERSON> is scheduled to return again
<DATE>June 18-27</DATE> to lead an entire Beethoven festival. The orchestra could name
<PERSON>Zinman</PERSON> principal guest conductor, which would make him a prime candidate to
succeed <PERSON>Herbert Blomstedt</PERSON>, music director since <DATE>1985</DATE>, should <PERSON>Blomstedt</PERSON> decide
to move on. Zinman is music director of the <LOCATION>Baltimore</LOCATION> Symphony.;   MUSICAL
NOTES -- KUSP-FM radio (88.9) in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION> got a leg up on the competition by
acquiring the exclusive <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> premiere broadcast rights for <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>' new
opera, "The Death of Klinghoffer." A recording of the world premiere in
<LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> <DATE>last March</DATE> will be broadcast <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at <TIME>10 a.m.</TIME> . . .;   Also at <LOCATION>Santa
Cruz</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Santa Cruz's McHenry Library</ORGANIZATION> is holding a
free public reception at <TIME>3 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Friday</DATE> to mark the acquisition of the archives
of local composer-conductor <PERSON>George Barati</PERSON>, 78. At the event, held in the
Special Collections area, the <ORGANIZATION>Porter String Quartet</ORGANIZATION> will give the world
premiere of <PERSON>Barati</PERSON>'s String Quartet No. 3.;   Artistic director and composer
<ORGANIZATION>Robert Greenberg of Composers Inc.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> complied fully with a
request from his publicity-minded board of directors. "They said, 'We need a
<LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION> angle,' " <PERSON>Greenberg</PERSON> explains. He wrote a new work for violin and
piano called -- "South Bay Angle.";   <PERSON>James Mobberley</PERSON>, featured at last
month's <ORGANIZATION>Composers Inc.</ORGANIZATION> concert, explained how he became a composer. Camping
out in <LOCATION>Bodega Bay</LOCATION> years ago, he found he couldn't sleep. "There were two
foghorns. I noticed that they were blowing a minor ninth (interval) apart, (in
a regular pattern of) 12 beats against 17.;   "I decided then that I had to
become a composer."  </TEXT>
