<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; RECORD; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  NEW classical compact discs keep tumbling out to the stores in record numbers.
Haven't those labels heard about the recession? If so, there's no sign of it
yet.;    Some of the best releases in the last month range from German
romantic music to modern works, and flamenco, too. They include the following:  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FLAMENCO GIVES INTRIGUING TURN TO MASS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Classical Recordings  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Misa Flamenca," by <PERSON>Paco Pena</PERSON> (Nimbus 5288; 41 minutes) --
<PERSON>Guitarist-composer Pena</PERSON> has created a rousing and deeply felt version of the
<LOCATION>Mass</LOCATION> in Spanish, using the flamenco idiom of singers, guitarists and
percussion. The most remarkable facet of this new recording is the guttural
flamenco singing, as in the powerful soul-searching "Our Father." Also of
note: the "Kyrie" guitar solo by <PERSON>Pena</PERSON>, the insistent thumping of an anguished
heart in "Lamb of God" and the catchy choral singing in the "Santo.";   
<PERSON>Pena</PERSON>'s work represents a new Hispanic dimension of the <ORGANIZATION>Catholic Mass</ORGANIZATION> and a new
liturgical use of timeless flamenco. One of the year's most intriguing
innovations.;    Works by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> composers; "American Elegies," Orchestra of <ORGANIZATION>St.
Luke</ORGANIZATION>'s, <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON>, conductor (Nonesuch 979249; 48 minutes, CD) -- The keenly
sensitive renditions here of works by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> composers add up to an elegant and
important record.;    Sweet-voiced soprano <PERSON>Dawn Upshaw</PERSON> could make grown men
melt with her tender group of <PERSON>Charles Ives</PERSON> songs, wistfully rendered in
conductor <PERSON>Adams</PERSON>' own arrangements.;    <PERSON>Ives</PERSON>' great orchestral enigma "The
Unanswered Question" is also here, followed by <PERSON>Adams</PERSON>' similarly meandering
"Eros Music," performed by pianist <PERSON>Paul Crossley</PERSON> and the orchestra.;    <PERSON>San
Franciscan Ingram Marshall</PERSON>'s environmental "Fog Tropes" includes taped marine
sounds of gaunt beauty. Here, too, are <PERSON>Morton Feldman</PERSON>'s minimalist "Madame
Press Died Last Week at Ninety" and <PERSON>David Diamond</PERSON>'s old-fashioned "Elegy in
Memory of <PERSON>Maurice Ravel</PERSON>.";    Anti-symphony; <PERSON>ANTON BRUCKNER</PERSON>: Symphony No. 0,
<ORGANIZATION>Frankfurt Radio Symphony Orchestra</ORGANIZATION>, Eliahu Inbal conducting, (<ORGANIZATION>Teldec</ORGANIZATION>
2292-46330; 44 minutes) -- I have a profound weakness for Austrian composer
<PERSON>Bruckner</PERSON>, whose romanticism, built on massive organ-like chords, can be
overwhelming. Symphonically he went at least one up on <LOCATION>Beethoven</LOCATION>; in addition
to <PERSON>Bruckner</PERSON>'s nine regularly numbered symphonies, he created the early and
little-played Symphony No. 0 in D Minor. The number was his own choice, by way
of rejecting the whole idea.;    Modern scholarship has shown its origins to
postdate the <ORGANIZATION>Symphony No. 1</ORGANIZATION>, in <DATE>1869</DATE>, coming at least five years after the
date once considered valid.;    To me, it's the first minimalist symphony,
with repetitive phrases producing nearly perpetual motion.;    The recording
is dreadful, the program notes almost incomprehensible. But the piece is
monumental, the melodiousness seductive. The youthful style and conciseness
are refreshing, a whole new dimension for those knowing only later Bruckner.
But for a better zero, go for <PERSON>Riccardo Chailly</PERSON>'s recording on London.;   
'<LOCATION>Leipzig</LOCATION>' version; <PERSON>ROBERT SCHUMANN</PERSON>: Symphonies Nos. 1, 4. <PERSON>Kurt Masur</PERSON> leads the
<LOCATION>London Philharmonic</LOCATION>. (<ORGANIZATION>Teldec</ORGANIZATION> 2292-46445; 56 minutes) -- <PERSON>Masur</PERSON> is on his home
turf with <PERSON>Schumann</PERSON>, propelling these works with an inexorable forcefulness, an
attention to structure and no frills.;    For the Fourth -- <PERSON>Schumann</PERSON>'s last --
<LOCATION>Leipzig</LOCATION> resident <PERSON>Masur</PERSON> opts for the first ("<LOCATION>Leipzig</LOCATION>") version, perhaps out of
chauvinism but more likely in concurrence with <PERSON>Brahms</PERSON> that it was the fresher
and tighter alternative. The orchestra plays with fine attention to detail.;  
 20th-century repertory;  <ORGANIZATION>American Piano Sonatas</ORGANIZATION>, Vol. 1: <LOCATION>Copland</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Ives</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Carter</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Barber</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Peter Lawson</PERSON>, piano (Virgin Classics 7 91163; 76 minutes) --
This release is very welcome, indeed, promising a whole series on timely
20th-century repertory.;    <PERSON>Lawson</PERSON> does wonders with <PERSON>Ives</PERSON>' rhythmically
unusual "Three-Page Sonata" (<DATE>1905</DATE>), in some ways the most modern work in the
group. The amiable and energetic <PERSON>Carter Sonata</PERSON> -- the longest on the CD --
helps frame the well-known <ORGANIZATION>Barber Op</ORGANIZATION>. 26 showpiece and <ORGANIZATION>Copland</ORGANIZATION>'s sensitive
Sonata of 1939-41.;    Sonically, this is a very attractive album. Look for
more to come. (Can we hope for an <PERSON>Ives</PERSON> "Concord" Sonata in Volume 2?)  </TEXT>
