<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congress Had First Quorum 200 Years Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> this week celebrates a curious but
important milestone: The 200th anniversary of the days on which the
first <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> and first <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and were finally
ready to begin the work of the new nation.
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> marks the occasion today, <DATE>April 4</DATE>, three days after
the actual <DATE>April 1</DATE> anniversary. The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> celebrates on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>,
<DATE>April 6</DATE>, the actual date of its first working quorum.
   Commemorative postage stamps will be issued honoring the
bicentennials of both houses.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> established under the Constitution first convened
in <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION> on <DATE>March 4, 1789</DATE>.
   But the absence of the required majority plus one prevented the
two chambers from getting down to business.
   On that first day only 13 of the 59 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> members and only eight
of the 22 senators were in attendance.
   Election complications, bad weather, muddy roads and just plain
sloth get the blame as causes for the delay.
   The journal of the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> noted with monotonous regularity that
``a quorum of the members not being present, the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> adjourned.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> under the discarded Articles of Confederation had been
noted for absenteeism and near paralysis, and many feared history
was about to repeat itself.
   ``We lose credit, spirit, everything,'' Rep. <PERSON>Fisher Ames</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> wrote to a friend in <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>. ``The public will forget
the government before it is born.''
   The senators who had managed to reach <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> wrote to their
absent colleagues: ``We apprehend that no arguments are necessary
to evince to you the indispensable necessity of putting the
government into immediate operation and, therefore ernestly request
that you will be so obliging as to attend as soon as possible.''
   George <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> had been elected the nation's first president,
but could not enter office until the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and
met to count the ballots of the <ORGANIZATION>Electoral College</ORGANIZATION>.
   From Mount Vernon he grumbled that senators and <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> members
were in a state of ``stupor or listlessness.''
   But eventually the required numbers assembled.
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>, counting its first quorum on <DATE>April 1 _ April</DATE> Fool's
Day some have noted _ elected <PERSON>Frederick Augustus Muhlenberg</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> as its first speaker.
   And <PERSON>Fisher Ames</PERSON>, much mollified now that work could begin, said
he was pleased with his new colleagues.
   While there were few ``shining geniuses,'' he said, there were
many who had ``experience, the virtues of the heart, and habits of
business.''
   On <DATE>April 6</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> counted its first quorum.
   The first order of business: Counting the votes of the electors
and dispatching messengers to inform <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON> that
they had indeed been chosen president and vice president.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> this week celebrates a curious but
important milestone: The 200th anniversary of the days on which the
first <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> and first <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and were finally
ready to begin the work of the new nation.
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> marks the occasion today, <DATE>April 4</DATE>, three days after
the actual <DATE>April 1</DATE> anniversary. The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> celebrates on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>,
<DATE>April 6</DATE>, the actual date of its first working quorum.
   Commemorative postage stamps will be issued honoring the
bicentennials of both houses.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> established under the Constitution first convened
in <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION> on <DATE>March 4, 1789</DATE>.
   But the absence of the required majority plus one prevented the
two chambers from getting down to business.
   On that first day only 13 of the 59 <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> members and only eight
of the 22 senators were in attendance.
   Election complications, bad weather, muddy roads and just plain
sloth get the blame as causes for the delay.
   The journal of the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> noted with monotonous regularity that
``a quorum of the members not being present, the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> adjourned.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> under the discarded Articles of Confederation had been
noted for absenteeism and near paralysis, and many feared history
was about to repeat itself.
   ``We lose credit, spirit, everything,'' Rep. <PERSON>Fisher Ames</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Massachusetts</LOCATION> wrote to a friend in <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION>. ``The public will forget
the government before it is born.''
   The senators who had managed to reach <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> wrote to their
absent colleagues: ``We apprehend that no arguments are necessary
to evince to you the indispensable necessity of putting the
government into immediate operation and, therefore ernestly request
that you will be so obliging as to attend as soon as possible.''
   George <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> had been elected the nation's first president,
but could not enter office until the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> achieved a quorum and
met to count the ballots of the <ORGANIZATION>Electoral College</ORGANIZATION>.
   From Mount Vernon he grumbled that senators and <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> members
were in a state of ``stupor or listlessness.''
   But eventually the required numbers assembled.
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION>, counting its first quorum on <DATE>April 1 _ April</DATE> Fool's
Day some have noted _ elected <PERSON>Frederick Augustus Muhlenberg</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Pennsylvania</LOCATION> as its first speaker.
   And <PERSON>Fisher Ames</PERSON>, much mollified now that work could begin, said
he was pleased with his new colleagues.
   While there were few ``shining geniuses,'' he said, there were
many who had ``experience, the virtues of the heart, and habits of
business.''
   On <DATE>April 6</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> counted its first quorum.
   The first order of business: Counting the votes of the electors
and dispatching messengers to inform <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and <PERSON>John Adams</PERSON> that
they had indeed been chosen president and vice president.
</TEXT>
